  "prompt": "Why is 2000 rupee note introduced and the 1000 rupee note is scraped? Why can't 1000 note also be changed to new ones like the 500?",
  "response": "The demonetization of \u20b9500 and \u20b91000 notes was a significant economic move by the Indian government in November 2016, led by Prime Minister Narendra Modi. Here are the key reasons:\n\nPrimary Objectives:\n1. Combat black money\n2. Reduce counterfeit currency\n3. Curb terror financing\n4. Promote digital transactions\n5. Increase tax compliance\n\nSpecific Rationale:\n- Most black money was stored in \u20b9500 and \u20b91000 denominations\n- These high-value notes were frequently used for illegal transactions\n- Significant number of counterfeit notes were in these denominations\n\nWhy \u20b92000 Note was Introduced:\n- To quickly replace high-value currency\n- Provide a higher denomination for convenience\n- Temporarily address cash shortage during demonetization\n\nWhy \u20b91000 Note was Discontinued:\n- To break existing black money cycles\n- Make it difficult to hoard large cash amounts\n- Reduce corruption and tax evasion\n\nLater, the \u20b92000 note was also gradually phased out (withdrawn from circulation in September 2023) as part of continuous monetary policy reforms.\n\nThe move was controversial but aimed at fundamental economic transformation and transparency.",
